4. Farmer phone in on cryptosporidiosis: 1st April: Sarah Thomson (Moredun postdoc on project) led a discussion and answered farmers questions in a live phone-in organised in collaboration with AHDB.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2015</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>86B7AC80-DF6C-4CD1-9BB1-02317DFB314E</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Policy &amp; public services</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>56d56910578424.97827649</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Agriculture, Food and Drink</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>We have successfully developed the first bovine organoid culture system. This has involved isolating intestinal crypts from bovine Ileal tissue, and propagating the consequent organoids in a custom-designed medium containing growth factors and inhibitors. The organoids are representative of all relevant cell types in gut tissue, grow and divide through the presence of intestinal stem cells, and can be passaged continuously (we have currently maintained organoids for at least 7 passages from isolation). Some validation steps have been completed to ensure that the organoids are (a) similar to normal ileal tissue and (b) their phenotype is stable over passage (qPCR of selected cell and tissue specific genes). We are in the process of continuing further validation (immunohistochemistry against relevant proteins and RNAseq to evaluate global gene expression patterns), but overall we have made significant progress, and should be in a position to asses whether the bovine intestinal organoids can be used to study host-pathogen interactions with Cryptosporidium parvum in vitro.
Additionally, we have begun characterising in detail the bovine neonatal immune response to C. parvum; this information is significantly lacking for the clinically relevant host.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The bovine organoid has several potential uses. Firstly, it provides a system for analysing any host-pathogen interaction in the bovine gut, making it a relevant platform for analysing many of the most economically important pathogens of livestock. The representation of all relevant cell types in the bovine gut also provide a significant benefit over, for example, purified primary cell monocultures. A further critical advantage is that these organoids are bovine-derived, meaning that the disadvantages of using model organisms are bypassed. Secondly, due to the ability to continuously passage the organoids, this system potentially paves the way for significant reduction of use of animals in research (as a project-specific example, analysing bovine epithelial cells currently requires fresh isolation and short-term maintenance of bovine primary cells from intestinal tissue).</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>4A1D7ED5-6239-4D33-B832-56A947C13727</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>56d566d2374256.12640270</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Agriculture, Food and Drink,Pharmaceuticals and Medical Biotechnology</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>12A84527-8B36-4289-83E1-A851F0D37FF8</gtr:id><gtr:title>Bovine cryptosporidiosis: impact, host-parasite interaction and control strategies.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Veterinary research</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/b596ee223e343a1e6b91bd673ff6c818"><gtr:id>b596ee223e343a1e6b91bd6